===Etymology 1===
Unclear. Possibly an [[areal]] word ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Compare {{cog|mro|||tr=rak|eldest brother}} and Kukish {{m|und||prak|eldest brother}} ({{zh-ref|Löffler, 1966}}), as well as {{cog|lhu|phâ||god; lord}} < {{cog|th|พระ|tr=prá}} < {{cog|okz|bra}} or {{cog|okz-ang|braḥ}}, {{m|okz|braḥh}}, {{m|okz|brah||[[distinguished]]; [[divine]]; [[excellent]]; [[holy]]; [[sacred]]; [[superior]]; etc.}} (see {{cog|km|ព្រះ|tr=preăh}} for more).

Possibly related to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*bʷaŋ ~ *pʷaŋ||(paternal) uncle; elder brother}}, in turn possibly related to {{och-l|兄|elder brother}} ({{zh-ref|Benedict, 1972}}).

Alternatively, from {{och-l|白|white}}; compare {{och-l|皤|white}}, which underwent parallel semantic shift to "white-haired", though this is possibly folk etymology ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Pronunciation 3 is the exoactive/transitive of pronunciation 1 ([[ibid.]]).

